Rules for Set Operators
Each SELECT statement must have the same number of columns.
Columns must have similar data types.
Columns must appear in the same order.

1️⃣ UNION Operator
Combines results from multiple SELECT queries and removes duplicate rows.

Query: Display all employee and manager records without duplicates
SELECT id, name, salary, department, dob FROM employee
UNION
SELECT id, manager_name, salary, department, dob FROM manager;

2️⃣ UNION ALL Operator
Combines results but keeps duplicate rows.
SELECT id, name, salary, department, dob FROM employee
UNION ALL
SELECT id, manager_name, salary, department, dob FROM manager;

3️⃣ EXCEPT (or MINUS) Operator
Returns rows in the first table but not in the second table.
Query: Employees who are NOT managers
SELECT id, name, salary, department, dob FROM employee
EXCEPT
SELECT id, manager_name, salary, department, dob FROM manager;

(In Oracle use MINUS instead of EXCEPT)

4️⃣ INTERSECT Operator
Returns common rows present in both tables.
Query: Employees who are also managers
SELECT id, name, salary, department, dob FROM employee
INTERSECT
SELECT id, manager_name, salary, department, dob FROM manager;

5️⃣ INTERSECT with Condition
Query: Employees who are managers where ID > 104
SELECT id, name, salary, department, dob FROM employee WHERE id > 104
INTERSECT
SELECT id, manager_name, salary, department, dob FROM manager;

✅ Summary of Set Operators
Operator	   Purpose
UNION	       Combines results and removes duplicates
UNION ALL	   Combines results and keeps duplicates
EXCEPT/MINUS   Returns rows in first query not in second
INTERSECT	   Returns common rows from both queries